						<div class="verses">
									<div id="vers154544" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">1</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Josias was eight years old when he came to the throne, and his reign at Jerusalem lasted thirty-one years; his motherâ€™s name was Idida, the daughter of Hadaia of Besecath.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154545" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">2</div>
						<div class="vers-content">He was obedient to the Lordâ€™s will, and followed in all things the example of his ancestor, king David, never swerving to right or left.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154546" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">3</div>
						<div class="vers-content">In the eighteenth year of his reign, Josias had an errand for the controller of the temple, Saphan, son of Aslia, son of Messula.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154547" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">4</div>
						<div class="vers-content">He was to bid the high priest Helcias reckon up the sum collected by the temple door-keepers for the needs of the Lordâ€™s house,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154548" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">5</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and pay it out to the workmen through the temple overseers. Pay must be given to these workmen, engaged on making good the temple fabric,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154549" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">6</div>
						<div class="vers-content">carpenters, masons, and builders alike; there was timber to be bought, too, and stone from the quarries, before the Lordâ€™s temple could be repaired.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154550" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">7</div>
						<div class="vers-content">No account need be kept of these expenses; the overseers could be trusted with full disposal of the money.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154551" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">8</div>
						<div class="vers-content">It was then that the high priest Helcias told Saphan he had found, there in the temple, a copy of the law, which he gave him to read.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154552" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">9</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And Saphan, going back to the king with news of his errand, to report that the temple offerings had been reckoned up and paid over to the temple overseers, for distribution to the workmen,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154553" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">10</div>
						<div class="vers-content">added that he had a book which the high priest Helcias had given him.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span>This book, then, Saphan read out in the royal presence;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154554" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">11</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and the king, upon hearing the terms of the Lordâ€™s law, rent his garments about him.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154555" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">12</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Then he gave his orders to Helcias, and Ahicam son of Saphan, and Achobor son of Micha, and Saphan the controller of the temple, and Asaia, one of his courtiers;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154556" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">13</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Go and consult the Lord, he told them, in my name, and in the name of this whole people of Juda, about this new-found copy of the law. Fiercely the Lordâ€™s anger burns against us, that the words of this book should have fallen on deaf ears, and our race should have disobeyed the commands enjoined upon us.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154557" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">14</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So Helcias, Ahicam, Achobor, Saphan and Asaia betook themselves to the prophetess Holda. She was wife to Sellum, son of Thecua, son of Araas, that once kept the royal wardrobe; her dwelling was at Jerusalem, in the new part of the city. So they told her their business,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154558" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">15</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and she, in return, gave them this message from the Lord God of Israel for the man that sent them:</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154559" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">16</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Thus says the Lord, For this city and its citizens I have punishments in store, all the punishments threatened in yonder book the king of Juda has read.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154560" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">17</div>
						<div class="vers-content">The men of Juda have forsaken me, and offered sacrifice to alien gods; all they do is done in defiance of me; the fire of my vengeance must needs break out against this city, and there is no quenching it.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154561" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">18</div>
						<div class="vers-content">But to the king of Juda, who sent you here to consult the Lord, give this message from the Lord God of Israel: Well for thee thou didst listen to the warnings this book gave thee!</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154562" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">19</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Well for thee that fear caught at thy heart, and thou didst humble thyself before the Lord, at hearing him threaten city and citizens with despair and doom; that thou didst rend thy garments, and hadst recourse to me in tears! And thou hast won my audience, the Lord says;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers154563" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">20</div>
						<div class="vers-content">I will lay thee to rest with thy fathers, in quiet times thou shalt go to thy grave; not for thy eyes to witness the great calamities I mean to bring on this city of thine.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
							</div>
